# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1778.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, when the Virginia General Assembly met to conduct the election, the incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was the only candidate nominated.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] By a joint resolution of the Senate and House of Delegates, balloting was dispensed with and Henry was declared re-elected by acclamation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 1, 1779.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Albemarle County Thomas Jefferson defeated the president of the Council of State John Page.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was ineligible for re-election due to term limits established by the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Virginia General Assembly in joint session.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] No candidate had a majority after the first count, requiring a second ballot between the two top-finishers.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 2, 1780.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Thomas Jefferson was re-elected.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Senate and the House of Delegates met separately on June 1 to nominate candidates for governor; more than one nomination was made, requiring a vote of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] When the Assembly met in joint session the following day, Jefferson was selected by the majority of members on the first ballot, although the names of the other candidates and the votes tallied were not recorded.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County was created in 1744 from the western portion of Goochland County, though portions of Albemarle were later carved out to create other counties.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County was named in honor of Willem Anne van Keppel, 2nd Earl of Albemarle.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Its most famous inhabitant was Thomas Jefferson, who built his estate home, Monticello, in the county.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] At the time of European encounter, the inhabitants of the area that became Albemarle County were a Siouan-speaking tribe called the Saponi.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] In 1744, the Virginia General Assembly created Albemarle County from the western portion of Goochland County.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The county was named in honor of Willem Anne van Keppel, 2nd Earl of Albemarle and titular Governor of Virginia at the time.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The large county was partitioned in 1761, forming Buckingham and Amherst counties, at which time the county seat was moved from the formerly central Scottsville to a piece of newly central land, christened Charlottesville.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] In 1777, Albemarle County was divided and Fluvanna County established, finalizing the boundaries of modern Albemarle County.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County is well known for its association with President and Founding Father Thomas Jefferson, who was born in the county at Shadwell, though it was then part of Goochland County.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] However, his home of Monticello is located in the county.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] When the American Revolutionary War started in 1775, Jefferson was made colonel of the Albemarle Militia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] During the Civil War, the Battle of Rio Hill was a skirmish in which Union cavalry raided a Confederate camp in Albemarle County, Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Until the Civil War, the majority of Albemarle County's population consisted of enslaved African Americans.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 726 square miles (1,880 km2), of which 721 square miles (1,870 km2) is land and 5 square miles (13 km2) (0.7%) is water.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The Rivanna River's south fork forms in Albemarle County and was historically important for transportation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The south fork flows in-between Darden Towe Park and Pen Park.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Boat ramp access is available at Darden Towe Park.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The James River acts as a natural border between Albemarle and Buckingham Counties.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle's western border with Augusta and Rockingham Counties is located within the Shenandoah National Park.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County borders eight other counties, more than any other county in Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 112,395.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 20.3% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.4% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] For every 100 females there were 91.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.1 males age 18 and over.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The racial makeup of the county was 72.8% White, 8.9% Black or African American, 0.3% American Indian and Alaska Native, 7.3% Asian, 0.0% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 3.6% from some other race, and 7.0% from two or more races.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 7.5% of the population.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 59.6% of residents lived in urban areas, while 40.4% lived in rural areas.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 43,468 households in the county, of which 28.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 28.1% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] About 28.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 47,291 housing units, of which 8.1% were vacant.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Among occupied housing units, 64.7% were owner-occupied and 35.3% were renter-occupied.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.6% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.0%.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The largest self-reported ancestry groups in Albemarle County are English 16.3%, German 16.0%, Irish 12.7%, "American" 11.4% and Italian 5.2%.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] As of the census of 2010, there were 98,970 people, 38,157 households, and 24,578 families residing in the county.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The population density was 137 people per square mile (53 people/km2).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 42,122 housing units at an average density of 58 units per square mile (22 units/km2).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The racial makeup of the county was 80.6% White, 9.7% Black or African American, 0.3% Native American, 4.7% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 2.3% from other races, and 2.4% from two or more races.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 5.5% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 38,157 households, out of which 28.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.4% were married couples living together, 9.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.6% were non-families.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 28.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 25.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The average household size was 2.41 and the average family size was 2.96.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] In the county, the population was spread out, with 21.5% under the age of 18, 12.3% from 18 to 24, 24.7% from 25 to 44, 27.2% from 45 to 64, and 14.3% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] For every 100 females there were 92.69 males.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] For every 100 females aged 18 and over, there were 89.59 males.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 22% of Albemarle residents have a graduate or professional degree, compared with 10% nationwide.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The median income for a household in the county was $63,001, and the median income for a family was $98,934.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Males had a median income of $55,530 versus $52,211 for females.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The per capita income for the county was $36,718.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] About 3.8% of families and 10.4% of the population were below the poverty line, including 8.0% of those under age 18 and 2.4% of those age 65 or over.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 35% of people working in Albemarle live in the county, while 65% commute in.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 19% of those commuting in live in Charlottesville, while the remainder live in the surrounding counties.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 26,800 people commute out of Albemarle for work.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] 48% of which commute to Charlottesville, making up 51% of Charlottesville's in-commuters.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] In 2022, Albemarle had a 2.7% unemployment rate, compared with a national rate of 3.6%.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle is governed by an elected six-member Board of Supervisors.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Management of the county is vested in a Board-appointed County Executive.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The nonpartisan School Board is also elected.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County has two branches of law enforcement, the Albemarle County Police Department, which handles criminal matters and is directed by the appointed police chief, Colonel Sean Reeves.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The second branch is the Albemarle County Sheriff's Office, which handles civil service in the county, and they are directed by the elected Sheriff Chan Bryant.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County Fire Rescue (ACFR) provides essential emergency services to the residents and visitors of Albemarle County including, fire suppression, emergency medical treatment, and transport, technical rescue, water rescue, and hazardous materials mitigation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] In addition, the department provides a wide array of non-emergency services such as investigations, business inspections, burn permits, child safety seat inspections, smoke detector installations, public education, and emergency management.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Services are provided through a combination of career staff, nine volunteer fire and rescue agencies, and regional partners.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The Albemarle County Sheriff's Office (ACSO) and the Albemarle County Police Department (ACPD) provide law enforcement services in the county.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The ACSO was created in 1745 when Joseph Thompson was appointed as the first sheriff.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Then in 1895, citizens started electing sheriffs for 4-year terms.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Lucian Watts was the first elected sheriff.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] As of 2022 the sheriff is Chan Bryant, the county's first woman sheriff.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Prior to 1983, local county governments could create a police force by a simple vote held by their respective board of supervisors.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] In February 1983 the Virginia General Assembly restricted the authority of county governments to create police forces without a voter referendum.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The law did not go into effect until July 1983: On May 11, 1983, before the law took effect, the Albemarle County Board of Supervisors passed an ordinance creating the Albemarle County Police Department.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] That original ordinance provided for a police chief and five full time officers.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] As of 2022 the chief of police is Sean Reeves.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The ACPD currently has 140 sworn officers, 23 civilian employees, and 3 animal control officers.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle is represented by Democrat Creigh Deeds in the Virginia State Senate; Democrats Katrina Callsen and Amy Laufer represent the county in the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Republican John McGuire represents most of the county in the U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Democrat Eugene Vindman represents a small sliver in the most northwestern portion of Albemarle County.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] For much of the second half of the 20th century, Albemarle County was heavily Republican, like most of this part of Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] However, the Republican edge narrowed significantly in the 1990s, in part due to the influence of the University of Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] In 2004, John Kerry carried it by two points, becoming the first Democrat to win the county since 1948.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] It swung hard to Barack Obama in 2008, and since then, it has become one of the few Democratic bastions in central Virginia, though it is not as overwhelmingly Democratic as Charlottesville.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The Albemarle County Public School System operates public education in the county.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] It provides education to nearly 14,000 students including preschool through high school.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The School Board and the Superintendent, Matthew Haas, work closely together in operating the Albemarle County Public School System.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Many private schools in Albemarle serve the county and students from surrounding areas.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Some students attend several private schools in the City of Charlottesville.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Jefferson-Madison Regional Library is the regional library system that provides services to the citizens of Albemarle.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Portions of the University of Virginia are located within Albemarle County.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] The city of Charlottesville is enclaved within Albemarle County.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Under Virginia law in effect since 1871, all municipalities in the state incorporated as cities are legally and politically independent of any county.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/albemarle-county-virginia] Many of these unincorporated areas have Charlottesville addresses.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The **Constitution of the Commonwealth of Virginia** is the document that defines and limits the powers of the state government and the basic rights of the citizens of the Commonwealth of Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Like all other state constitutions, it is supreme over Virginia's laws and acts of government, though it may be superseded by the United States Constitution and U.S. federal law as per the Supremacy Clause.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The original Virginia Constitution of 1776 was enacted at the time of the Declaration of Independence by the first thirteen states of the United States of America.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Virginia was an early state to adopt its own Constitution on June 29, 1776, and the document was widely influential both in the United States and abroad.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In addition to frequent amendments, there have been six major subsequent revisions of the constitution (by Conventions for the constitutions of 1830, 1851, 1864, 1870, 1902, and by commission for 1971 amendments).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] These new constitutions have been part of, and in reaction to, periods of major regional or social upheaval in Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] For instance, the 1902 constitution included provisions to disenfranchise African Americans, who in 1900 made up nearly 36% of the state's population.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] They did not regain suffrage until after the enactment of federal civil rights legislation in the mid-1960s.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The drafting of the first Virginia Constitution began in early 1776, amidst the American colonies' break with Britain.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] George Mason and James Madison played central roles in shaping the document.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Although Thomas Jefferson submitted a draft from the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia, it arrived too late to be considered.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Madison's involvement in Virginia’s founding charter would later inform his work on the United States Constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Jefferson later criticized the final version, arguing it lacked sufficient structural checks and failed to secure a truly balanced republican government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Adopted on June 29, 1776, the Constitution formally dissolved Virginia’s allegiance to the British crown and accused King George III of tyranny.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] It created a bicameral legislature—the General Assembly—and established a weak executive branch, with a governor elected annually by the legislature.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The accompanying Virginia Declaration of Rights, drafted by Mason, outlined core political principles, including the inherent rights of individuals and the fundamental purpose of government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Declaration of Independence and later served as a model for the U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] While revolutionary in tone, the 1776 Constitution preserved many aspects of colonial governance.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Drawing on Enlightenment philosophy—especially John Locke's theories of natural rights—the framers emphasized legislative supremacy and separation of powers, though in practice most authority remained in the General Assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Both the executive and judiciary were appointed by the legislature, creating little institutional independence.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Historian Brent Tarter argues this structure "entrenched the power of the landed gentry" and ensured continued dominance by Virginia’s elite families.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Representation was based on fixed counties rather than population, disproportionately empowering eastern slaveholding regions over growing western settlements.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Suffrage was limited to white male property owners, excluding most Virginians from political participation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] It was also silent on slavery, leaving the institution legally untouched—an omission that, according to Tarter, signaled tacit approval.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Despite these limitations, the Constitution of 1776 significantly influenced other revolutionary governments.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Wood describes it as a blueprint for state-building, particularly in its emphasis on written rights declarations and legislative dominance, although later generations would criticize the imbalance of power it created.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Legal scholar Stephen McCullough observes that courts have since interpreted the document as coextensive with federal constitutional protections, often neglecting the unique rights and traditions rooted in Virginia's own legal history.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] He argues that “preserving the vitality of the Virginia Constitution depends on active interpretation,” and calls for greater scholarly and judicial engagement with its original meaning.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] By the 1820s, Virginia was one of only two states that limited voting to landowners.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In addition, because representation was by county rather than population, the residents of increasingly populous Western Virginia (the area that would become West Virginia in 1863) had grown discontented at their limited representation in the legislature.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Pressure increased until a constitutional convention was convened in 1829–1830.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] This convention became largely a contest between eastern Virginia planters of the slaveholding elite and the less affluent yeomen farmers of Western Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Issues of representation and suffrage dominated the debate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Delegates to the convention included such prominent Virginians as James Madison, James Monroe, John Tyler, and John Marshall.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Western leaders included Philip Doddridge and Alexander Campbell.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The convention ultimately compromised by loosening suffrage requirements.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] It also reduced the number of senators and delegates to the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The resulting constitution was ratified by a popular majority, though most of the voters in the western part of the state ended up voting against it.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Thus, the underlying intrastate tensions remained, and would have to be addressed later.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] As of the 1840 census, the majority of the white residents of the state lived in western Virginia, but they were underrepresented in the legislature because of the continued property requirement for voting; not all held sufficient property to vote.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] This compounded their dissatisfaction with the apportionment scheme adopted in 1830, which was based on counties rather than population, thus giving disproportionate power to the fewer, but propertied whites who lived in the eastern part of the state and kept a grip on the legislature.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] As the state legislature also elected the governor and the United States senators, Western Virginians felt they had little influence on state leadership.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Their attempts to win electoral reform in the Virginia legislature were defeated each time.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Some began to openly discuss the abolition of slavery or secession from the state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Ultimately, the eastern planters could not continue to ignore their discontent, and a new constitutional convention was called to resolve the continuing tensions.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The most significant change adopted in the 1851 Constitution was elimination of the property requirement for voting, resulting in extension of the suffrage to all white males of voting age.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The 1851 Constitution established popular election for the governor, the newly created office of lieutenant governor, and all Virginia judges, rather than the election of the top two state officers by the legislature, or political appointment for judges.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Because of these changes, the 1851 Virginia Constitution became known as the "Reform Constitution".
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] When in 1861, the Virginia legislature voted for secession in the events leading up to the American Civil War, all of the western and several of the northern counties dissented.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] They set up a separate government with Francis H.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] During the Civil War, this separate or "restored" government approved the creation of West Virginia as a separate state (which was admitted to the Union in 1863) and in 1864 it approved a new Constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The constitution was the product of a divided state and government; it was the first since the original 1776 Constitution to be adopted by the legislature without a popular vote.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The 1864 Constitution abolished slavery in Virginia, disenfranchised men who had served in the Confederate government, recognized the creation of the State of West Virginia, and adjusted the number and terms of office of the members of the Virginia Assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The foreword to the current Virginia Constitution does not include the 1864 Constitution in its list of previous constitutions.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] It notes that the 1864 Constitution was drafted under wartime conditions and was of uncertain legal status.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] After the end of the Civil War, Virginia came briefly under military rule during Reconstruction, with the district commanded by John M.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Pursuant to federal Reconstruction legislation, Schofield called for a new constitutional convention to meet in Richmond from December 1867 to April 1868.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In protest of freedmen's suffrage, many of Virginia's conservative whites refused to participate in voting for delegates.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] As a result, Republicans led by Judge John Curtiss Underwood dominated the convention.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Opponents called the result the "Underwood Constitution" or the "Negro Constitution", as it gave freedmen suffrage.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Controversy over clauses that continued the temporary disenfranchisement of former Confederate government members delayed the adoption of the Constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] An eventual compromise provided for separate voting disenfranchisement clauses and the rest of the Constitution; the former failed to win approval.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The remainder of the Underwood Constitution was ratified by a popular vote of 210,585 to 9,136 and went into effect in 1870.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In the late nineteenth century, white Democrats regained power in state legislatures across the South.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] They passed Jim Crow laws establishing racial segregation in public facilities and restricting the lives of blacks.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] By the turn of the 20th century, six Southern states had essentially eliminated the black vote, and pressure mounted among whites in Virginia to do the same, ostensibly as a way to stop electoral fraud and corruption.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The 1901 constitutional convention met in this climate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Members were focused on restricting black voting rights without violating the Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution or disenfranchising poor whites.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Led by the future Senator Carter Glass, the convention created requirements that all prospective voters had to pay poll taxes or pass a literacy test administered by white registrars.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] An exemption was granted, in a kind of grandfather clause, for military veterans and sons of veterans, who were virtually all white.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The changes effectively disenfranchised black voters, though many illiterate whites were also unable to meet the new requirements.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In 1900 blacks made up nearly 36 percent of the population.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In succeeding elections, the Virginia electorate was reduced by nearly half as a result of the changes.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] When adjusted for the Nineteenth Amendment, voter turnout would not return to 1900 levels until 1952 within a statewide population almost twice the size.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The small electorate was key to maintaining the dominant Democratic Organization in power for sixty years.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Other significant provisions of the 1902 Constitution imposed racial segregation in public schools (which already existed on a *de facto* basis) and abolished the county court system.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The Constitution provided for the creation of the State Corporation Commission to regulate the growing power of the railroads.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Because of concern over African American opposition, the convention did not honor its pledge to have the proposed constitution put to popular vote.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Like the 1864 Constitution by the Loyalist government during the Civil War, the legislature adopted the 1902 Constitution without ratification by the electorate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] It was in effect far longer than any previous Virginia constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] As a result of the Civil Rights Movement's challenging the restrictions and discrimination practiced against blacks' exercise of constitutional rights, a series of US Supreme Court cases, beginning with *Brown v.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Board of Education* in 1954, the 24th Amendment, and federal legislation: the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965 had overturned the most controversial aspects of the 1902 Constitution – the provisions restricting voting by African Americans and mandating school segregation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Combined with the election of Governor Mills Godwin in 1965, there was impetus for governmental change.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Godwin strongly advocated the loosening of the strict constitutional restrictions on state-issued bonds and borrowing and used his power and popularity to push for a new constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In 1968 a joint resolution of the Virginia General Assembly approved a new commission, chaired by former Governor Albertis Harrison, to revise the constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The Commission on Constitutional Revision presented its report and recommendations to Governor Godwin and the General Assembly in January 1969, and continued to work with them to draft a final consensus version.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The proposed Constitution was overwhelmingly approved by the voters of Virginia (who by then included African American men and women, following passage of federal civil rights legislation in the mid-1960s) and took effect on July 1, 1971.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Since 1971, additional amendments have been passed by the General Assembly and approved by the voters to conform to provisions in the U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Supreme Court and Congressional statute.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The voting age has been reduced to eighteen, voting residency requirements have been removed, and voter registration conforms to the Motor Voter Act.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Additionally, the Virginia Constitution now provides for a General Assembly session following a governor's veto, and the right of the people to hunt, fish and harvest game is guaranteed.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In 2006, Virginians passed an amendment limiting marriage to "unions between one man and one woman".
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] That has since been overturned by *Obergefell v.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Hodges* (2015), which legalized same-sex marriage throughout the United States.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article I contains the entire original Virginia Declaration of Rights from the 1776 Constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Several of the sections have been expanded to incorporate concepts from the United States Bill of Rights, including the right to due process, the prohibition against double jeopardy, and the right to bear arms.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Like the Federal Constitution, the Virginia Bill of Rights, in §17, states that the listing of certain rights is not to be construed to exclude other rights held by the people.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In 1997, a Victims' Rights Amendment was added to the Virginia Bill of Rights as §8-A.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Commonwealth,* the only case so far to interpret this amendment, the Virginia Supreme Court used the Victims's Rights Amendment to support its ruling that an alleged rape victim could not be compelled to submit to a psychiatric evaluation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] On November 7, 2006, Virginia voters ratified an amendment, previously approved by the General Assembly, prohibiting same-sex marriage, to be added to the Bill of Rights.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The amendment was declared to be in violation the United States Constitution by a U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] District Court Judge on February 13, 2014.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The second Article of the Constitution sets out the procedures and mechanisms for voting, elections and holding office.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Pursuant to Section 1, any Virginia resident over age 18 may vote in state elections; the voting age was reduced from 21 by a 1972 amendment to the federal constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] However, § 1 denies the vote to people who have been determined to be mentally incompetent or anyone convicted of a felony.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Disfranchising convicted felons has been found to be consistent with the Equal Protection Clause of the U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The General Assembly, pursuant to §4, is given wide power to regulate the time, place, and manner of all elections.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] §5 establishes that the only qualifications to hold office in Virginia are that a person must have been a Virginia resident for at least one year and eligible to vote.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Any statute or rule requiring other qualifications is constitutionally invalid under this section.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] But, the General Assembly can impose local residency requirements for election to local governmental bodies or for election to the Assembly in representation of particular districts.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article III has one section, confirming the principle of separation of powers between the legislative, executive and judicial branches of government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Unlike the U.S. federal Constitution, the Virginia Constitution explicitly provides that no branch may exercise powers that properly belong to the others.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Separation between the branches of government is also listed as a right of the people in §5 of Article I.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article IV establishes the basic structure and authority of the Virginia legislature.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The legislative power of the state is vested in the Virginia General Assembly, which consists of the Virginia Senate and the Virginia House of Delegates. §17 of Article IV gives the legislature the power to impeach members of the executive and judicial branches.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The original §14 of Article IV forbade the incorporation of churches, though the Virginia Commission on Constitutional Revision, in its 1969 report, had recognized that the prohibition was probably invalid.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The federal district court for the Western District of Virginia ruled in April 2002 that this provision of the Virginia Constitution was in fact unconstitutional, because it violates the federal constitutional right to the free exercise of religion.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The court found that it is unconstitutional to deny a church the option to incorporate under state law when other groups can incorporate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The Virginia Constitution was subsequently amended to remove the restriction.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The fifth Article similarly defines the structure and powers of the executive branch.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The Governor of Virginia is invested as the chief executive, though §1 of Article V, provides that the governor may not run for successive terms.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The offices of lieutenant governor and attorney general are established as supporting elected constitutional positions.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The constitutional powers of the governor include the ability to sign legislation, veto bills (which veto may then be overridden by a two-thirds majority of both houses of the assembly), and issue pardons.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article VI vests judicial power in the Supreme Court of Virginia, along with the subordinate courts created by the General Assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Judges are appointed by a majority vote in the General Assembly to terms of 12 years for Supreme Court Justices and 8 years for other judges.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The Supreme Court, pursuant to §5, has the authority to make rules governing the practice of law and procedures in the courts of the commonwealth (see rules), and the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court is established as the administrative head of the Virginia judicial system.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article VII of the Constitution sets up the basic framework for the structure and function of local government in Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Local government may be established at the town (population over 1000), city (population over 5000), county or regional government level.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article VII gives the General Assembly the power to create general laws for the organization and governing of these political subdivisions, except that regional governments cannot be created without the consent of the majority of the voters who vote on the issue in the region.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Section 4 establishes the constitutional offices of treasurer, sheriff, Commonwealth's Attorney, clerk of court and Commissioner of the Revenue to be elected within each city and county in Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] A compulsory and free primary and secondary public education for every Virginia child is the focus of Article VIII.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The General Assembly is empowered to determine the funding for the educational system and apportion the cost between state and local government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] A state Board of Education is established to create school divisions and effectuate the overall educational policies.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Supervision of the individual schools is delegated to local school boards, provided for in §7.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The primary purpose of Article IX is to create the Virginia State Corporation Commission, which is charged with administering the laws that regulate corporations.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The State Corporation Commission also issues charters for Virginia corporations and licenses to do business for "foreign" (non-Virginia) corporations.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Section 5 of Article IX prohibits such foreign corporations from doing anything in Virginia that a Virginia corporation could not do.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article X establishes the basic structure for taxation of personal property in Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Pursuant to this Article, all non-exempt real and personal property is subject to taxation at its fair market value.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Section 6 sets out a lengthy list of exempt property, which includes church property, cemeteries, and non-profit school property.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Significant additions to Article X include §7, a budget amendment, which became effective in 1986, and §7-A, which establishes the "Lottery Proceeds Fund", requiring that all proceeds from the lottery be set aside for educational purposes.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Article XI states that it is the general policy of the Commonwealth to preserve, protect and conserve the state's natural and historic resources.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The General Assembly is permitted to further these policies by entering into public-private partnerships or partnerships with federal agencies.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] A 2001 amendment added §4, which establishes hunting and fishing as constitutional rights of Virginians, though the legislature may enact appropriate regulations and restrictions on these rights.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The last Article creates the mechanism for future changes to the Constitution.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Any amendment to the Constitution must first be passed by a majority in each of the two legislative houses.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The proposed amendment must then be held over for consideration by the succeeding elected legislature, where it must again be passed by a majority in each house.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] The amendment then goes on the general ballot and becomes enacted into the Constitution if approved by a majority of the voters.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Alternatively, a two-thirds vote of both Virginia houses may call for the creation of a constitutional convention.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Any revisions or amendments proposed by the constitutional convention are presented to the citizens of Virginia and become law upon approval by a majority of voters.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] There is a perennial discussion over Virginia's unique Constitutional status restricting its governor to one consecutive term, and its method of selecting both trial and appellate judges by state legislature, shared only with South Carolina.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] Since the current constitution was ratified, there have been 53 amendments added to the constitution, concerning issues ranging from tax exemptions and voting rules to budgeting and legislative calendars.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/constitution-of-virginia] In 2020, the state redistricting process was dramatically reshaped, establishing a bipartisan redistricting commission with judicial oversight.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Voters do not register by party in Virginia, and Virginia conducts open primaries where any voter may cast a ballot for either party.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Traditionally, political parties could choose which nomination method to use for each election, with the option to either participate in the state-run primary or conduct a party-run convention.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] A law which passed in 2021 and took effect in 2024 requires a party's method of nomination to make certain accommodations for absentee voters, and had the practical effect of outlawing party-run conventions.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In general elections, the party affiliations of local candidates do not appear on the ballot.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Candidates for federal, statewide, and General Assembly offices appear on the ballot with party designations.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Besides the Democratic Party of Virginia and the Republican Party of Virginia, other parties include the Libertarian Party of Virginia, Constitution Party of Virginia, Green Party of Virginia, and the Independent Greens of Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Third parties and independents have benefited from electoral reform in Virginia, especially streamlined ballot access, and have made their presence known by appearing on statewide ballots and even winning seats to soil and water conservation district boards.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2009, Governor Tim Kaine proposed to authorize no-excuse early voting in Virginia elections, noting that 26 other states allow it.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] On January 26, 2009, the bill passed the Democratic-controlled Senate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] However, the Republican-controlled House of delegates killed the proposal.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Governor Kaine worked with a coalition of civic groups to work to restore the voting rights of felons who were convicted of non-violent crimes in the past.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Kaine's staff reviewed each individual application from felons who had been out of prison for at least five years without an additional conviction.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] An estimated 366,000 Virginia citizens are disenfranchised due to a prior felony conviction.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Commonwealth of Virginia holds its state general elections on the first Tuesday after the first Monday in November (better known as Election Day) in every odd-numbered year.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] As a result of this, gubernatorial elections in Virginia systematically follow the quadrennial United States presidential election by one year.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] During general elections in Virginia, elections are held for the statewide executive positions of governor, lieutenant governor, and attorney general.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Elections are also held for legislative positions in the Senate of Virginia and the Virginia House of Delegates and the county-level offices of Commonwealth's attorney, sheriff, clerk of court, Treasurer, and Commissioner of the Revenue.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Officials elected to the House of Delegates serve a term of two years, and clerks of court are elected to eight-year terms.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] All other officials are elected for a term of four years.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia's governor, lieutenant governor, and attorney general are elected at large every four years.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] State senators and members of the House of Delegates are elected in single-member districts.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] County-level officials are elected by county.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia has 100 seats in its House of Delegates, and 40 seats in its Senate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] After the American Civil War (1861–1865), Virginia was in political turmoil.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] 48 former counties now in West Virginia were gone, soon to be joined by two more.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Commonwealth of Virginia unsuccessfully appealed to the U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the remaining area, many citizens, mostly males of African American heritage, were newly enfranchised to vote.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Many others, primarily former Confederates, were initially disenfranchised.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Elections resumed after 5 years as a U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Military District, and control was chaotic.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the late 1870s, a coalition of Conservative Democrats, Republicans, and African Americans was assembled and the Readjuster Party took power for about 10 years.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Senator William Mahone and the Readjuster Party lost control of Virginia politics around 1883, white Democrats regained the state legislature.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] They proceeded to use statute and a new constitution in 1901, with provisions such as a poll tax, residency requirements, and literacy test to disfranchise most African Americans and many poor whites.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Their disfranchisement lasted until after the passage of civil rights legislation in the mid-1960s.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] White Democrats created a one-party state, with a nearly unchallenged majority of state and most federal offices through the middle of the 20th century.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Byrd Organization headed by Harry F.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Byrd Sr. largely controlled statewide politics.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Through their leadership and activism in the Civil Rights Movement, African Americans gained national support for passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which provided Federal oversight and enforcement to maintain all citizens' ability to vote.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act, decisions affecting elections are subject to preclearance by the U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Department of Justice before they can take effect.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] President Lyndon Johnson's and national Democrats' support for civil rights turned many conservative whites in Virginia against the Democrats.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] However, many Virginians had been willing to support Republicans, at least at the national level, since the 1930s due to Franklin Roosevelt's strong support for organized labor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] While the Republican Party in most of the South tended to attract right-wing conservatives like Jesse Helms and Strom Thurmond, Virginia's GOP has tended to be more moderate by regional standards.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The state elected moderate Republican A.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Linwood Holton Jr. in 1970; Holton became the first Republican governor in the 20th century, effectively ending the influence of the Byrd Organization.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The current Virginia State Constitution was created in 1971 to replace the discriminatory one created in 1901.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Holton was succeeded by two other Republican governors: the more conservative Mills Godwin (a former Democrat) and John N.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Senator John Warner and Congressman Tom Davis also exemplified the more "moderate-conservative" tendencies of Virginia Republicans.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] From 1982 through 1994, Democrats served as governor, with Chuck Robb elected in 1981 and Gerald L.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 1989, Virginia elected Democrat Douglas Wilder governor, who served from 1990 to 1994, as Virginia's first African-American governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2001, Virginia elected Democrats Mark Warner as governor and Tim Kaine as lieutenant governor, and Kaine was elected to succeed Warner as governor in 2005.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2009, however, a Republican again returned to the governor's mansion as Bob McDonnell defeated Democrat Creigh Deeds, garnering 58.61% of the popular vote to Deeds' 41.25%.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Republicans also managed to sweep all statewide races in 2009, the first time they accomplished this feat since 1997.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia voted for Republicans in nearly every presidential election from 1952 to 2004 except for the Democratic landslide in President Johnson's election in 1964.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] This former streak started when Richard Nixon began the Southern Strategy, and is the longest among the former Confederate States.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia was the only such state to vote for Gerald Ford over Jimmy Carter in 1976.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Since 2008, Virginia has voted for Democrats in presidential elections, including Barack Obama; in 2016, Virginia was the only former Confederate state to vote for Hillary Clinton over Donald Trump.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 1989, Doug Wilder was the first African-American elected governor of a U.S. state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Despite Virginia's support of Republican presidential candidates and reputation as a conservative state, voters elected Democratic candidates for three consecutive gubernatorial races in the 1980s.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In addition, Democratic representatives maintained large majorities in both houses of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Many Democratic state representatives from rural and suburban districts had conservative stances on various issues.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the 1990s Virginia experienced some political realignment, electing conservative Republicans George Allen and Jim Gilmore to the governorship from 1994 until 2002.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Jim Gilmore's "no car tax" pledge was emblazoned on bumper stickers and yard signs across the state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Republicans captured both houses of the General Assembly and built majorities.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Republican representatives replaced Conservative and moderate Democrats from rural and suburban areas.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Within the Republican party, more conservative officeholders supplanted the remnants of the less conservative "mountain-valley" faction of Holton, so named because many members were from the Shenandoah Valley and Southwest Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] After eight years of Republican governorships, in 2001, Mark Warner, a progressive businessman, won the governorship and confronted budget difficulties related to the recession by cutting money from all state departments.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia's executive branch is limited by the fact that governors are barred from serving consecutive terms, a constitutional provision that distinguishes Virginia from any other state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] After decades of Democratic rule in the Virginia General Assembly, Republicans took control around the turn of the 21st century and promptly redistricted to protect their incumbents.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2005 Tim Kaine, Warner's lieutenant governor, won the governor's office over Jerry Kilgore and "independent Republican" state senator Russ Potts.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2006, Jim Webb narrowly defeated George Allen in the wake of the Macaca slur incident.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The electorate's reaction to Allen's gaffe demonstrated the changing sensibilities of the region's citizens; prior to that, Allen had a double-digit lead in the polls.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2007, Virginia driver fees legislation created a political uproar when residents realized that they faced $3,000 fines for certain moving violations.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] An online petition quickly gathered hundreds of thousands of signatures, spurring legislators up for re-election that November to reconsider their positions.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] This was the first time that the Internet played such a dramatic role in influencing Virginia politics.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2007, the Democrats regained control of the State Senate, and narrowed the Republican majority in the House of delegates to 7 or 8 votes.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia voted for Democrat Barack Obama in 2008, after backing Republican candidates for the previous ten presidential elections.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia may be considered a "swing state" for future presidential elections.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Its margin for Obama of 6.3% made it a close indicator of the national vote (a 7.2% Obama margin).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the November 2009 general election Republican Bob McDonnell won the governorship by an 18-point margin, while Republican lieutenant governor and Attorney General candidates Bill Bolling and Ken Cuccinelli also won their respective races.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] They led statewide gains by the Republican party winning five additional seats in the House of Delegates.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the November 2010 federal elections, Republicans picked up three U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] House seats previously held by Democrats, and proceeded to hold eight of Virginia's eleven seats, compared to three for Democrats.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the November 2018 federal elections, Democrats picked up three U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] House seats previously held by Republicans, and proceeded to hold seven of Virginia's eleven seats, compared to four for Republicans.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] From 1977 until 2013, Virginia had elected a governor of the opposite political party compared to the President of the United States of the time.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2017, Virginia returned to electing a governor of the opposite political party compared to the current President by electing Ralph Northam.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] This happened again when Glenn Youngkin was elected in 2021.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The following table lists all state and federal regular elections from 1976, along with the voter turnout.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Northern Virginia has favored Democratic candidates in recent elections.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the 2004 United States presidential election, John Kerry won Fairfax County, long a Republican stronghold, by 2.4% and generally fared better in the rest of Northern Virginia than Al Gore did in 2000.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Despite this increase, however, he still lost every other county except Arlington County in Northern Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In contrast to the changing voting trend in Northern Virginia, the majority of the rest of Virginia has been supportive of the Republican Party.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Some portions of the state like college towns and the southeastern counties in the Black Belt Region have been more likely to vote Democratic.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2005 and 2006, Democrats Tim Kaine (running for governor) and Jim Webb (in a race for Senator) won nearly all jurisdictions within the Northern Virginia region.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Alexandria resident Mark Warner had not won so many jurisdictions when winning the governorship in 2001.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] By contrast, Warner performed comparatively strongly in rural areas, particularly Southwest Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] His campaign stressed respect for rural cultural values (such as gun rights) and strategies for economic development.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the state's largest city, Virginia Beach (pop.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] 450,000), most elected officials are Republicans.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] However, most elected officials in the state's most populous county, Fairfax County (pop.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Republican Party's strongholds are in the counties of Southwest Virginia, exurban Northern Virginia counties like Stafford, and Richmond suburbs like Hanover County.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Democrats are dominant in the inner suburbs of Northern Virginia, the city of Charlottesville and its suburbs in Albemarle County, and industrial Hampton Roads cities of Norfolk, Portsmouth, Newport News, and Hampton, and also the city of Richmond.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The three most significant "swing districts" are Loudoun and Prince William counties in Northern Virginia and Henrico County in the Richmond suburbs.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] All three of these "swing" counties voted for President George W.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Democrats have won formerly Republican-held seats in the General Assembly in Loudoun and Prince William counties in the 2017 and 2019 elections.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The **governor of the Commonwealth of Virginia** is the head of government of the Commonwealth of Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor is head of the executive branch of the government of Virginia and is the commander-in-chief of the Virginia National Guard and Virginia Defense Force.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Three signatories of the Declaration of Independence served as governor of Virginia and three governors became president of the United States: Thomas Jefferson, James Monroe, and John Tyler.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The current officeholder is Abigail Spanberger, a member of the Democratic Party who took office on January 17, 2026.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] She is Virginia's first female governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Unlike other state governors, Virginia governors are not allowed to serve consecutive terms.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] They have been barred from immediate re-election since the adoption of Virginia's second constitution, in 1830.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] However, a former governor is permitted to run for a second term in a future election.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Only two governors since 1830, William Smith and Mills Godwin, have been elected to additional terms.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Smith's second term came after Virginia seceded from the Union, while Godwin became the first ever governor in American history to be elected by both major parties when the former Democrat was elected in 1973 as a Republican.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The only other governors to serve non-consecutive terms in office are Patrick Henry and James Monroe, with George William Smith serving twice as acting governor before becoming official governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] To get on the ballot for governor of Virginia, each candidate must file 10,000 signatures, including the signatures of at least 400 qualified voters from each of the 11 congressional districts in the Commonwealth.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor is the head of government in Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] At the beginning of every regular session, they must report the state of the Commonwealth to the Virginia General Assembly (both the House of Delegates and the Senate).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] They must convene the legislature when two-thirds of each house calls for a special session.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor must ensure that the laws of the Commonwealth are faithfully executed by either signing, or allowing it to come into law, or vetoing, not allowing it to become law.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] They are responsible for the safety of the state, as they serve as commander-in-chief of the Virginia Militia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Established by Article V, Section 16 of the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The position of governor of Virginia dates back to the 1607 first permanent English settlement in America, at Jamestown on the north shore of the James River upstream from Hampton Roads harbor at the mouth of the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The Virginia Company of London set up a government-run by a council.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The president of the council served as a governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The council was based in London and controlled the colony from afar.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Nominally, Thomas Smith was the first president of the council, but he never left England.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Edward Maria Wingfield was the first president of the council in residence in the new province, making him the first to exercise the actual authority of governing Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The Virginia Company soon abandoned governance by council two years after the landing on May 23, 1609, and replacing it with a governor, John Smith (1580–1631).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] In 1624, the English monarchy of King James I (1566–1625, reigned 1603–1625), in the last year of his reign, of the royal House of Stuart took control from the Virginia Company and its stockholders and made Virginia a crown colony.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Governors continued to be appointed by the monarch for many years.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Most often, the appointed governor would reside in England while a deputy or lieutenant governor exercised authority.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Virginia became an independent sovereign state and Commonwealth during the American Revolutionary War (1775–1783), with Patrick Henry (1736–1799, served 1776–1779 and 1786–1789) as its first governor (and also later sixth).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] From the Revolution until 1851, the governor was elected by the General Assembly of Virginia (commonwealth/state legislature).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] After 1851, in a democratic trend spreading across the Union, the state turned to popular elections for office holders.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] During the American Civil War (1861–1865), Francis Harrison Pierpont was the governor of the Union-controlled parts of the state, later of which emerged the new state in the northwest of West Virginia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Pierpont also served as one of the provisional governors during the post-war Reconstruction era.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] These governors were appointed by the Federal government of the President and U.S.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Congress, both controlled by Radical Republicans for a decade.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] In 1874, Virginia regained its right to self-governance and elected James L.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Kemper (1823–1895), a Democrat and temporary Conservative Party member and former Confederate general as governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] After the Radical Republican appointees of the post-war Reconstruction era, Virginia would not actually elect another regular Republican as governor until A.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Cameron was elected governor under the banner of the Readjuster Party, a coalition of Republicans and populist Democrats.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Douglas Wilder became the first elected and only the second African American Governor of any U.S. state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] He served as governor from 1990 to 1994.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The only exception being in 2013 with the election of Democrat Terry McAuliffe, following the re-election of President Obama in 2012.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Tim Kaine was inaugurated on January 14, 2006.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Due to renovations on the Capitol in Richmond, his inauguration was held in Williamsburg, making him the first governor to be inaugurated in Williamsburg since Thomas Jefferson in 1779.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The current governor of Virginia is Abigail Spanberger who was inaugurated on January 17, 2026.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor of Virginia is addressed as "The Honorable" but may occasionally be referred to as "Excellency" if ceremonially appropriate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A **governor** is an administrative leader and head of a polity or political region, in some cases, such as governors-general, as the head of a state's official representative.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Depending on the type of political region or polity, a *governor* may be either appointed or elected, and the governor's powers can vary significantly, depending on the public laws in place locally.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The adjective pertaining to a governor is **gubernatorial**, from the Latin root *gubernare*.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In a federated state, the governor may serve as head of state and head of government for their regional polity, while still operating under the laws of the federation, which has its own head of state for the entire federation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Though the legal and administrative framework of provinces, each administered by a governor, was created by the Romans, the term *governor* has been a convenient term for historians to describe similar systems in antiquity.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Indeed, many regions of the pre-Roman antiquity were ultimately replaced by Roman 'standardized' provincial governments after their conquest by Rome.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Plato used the metaphor of turning the Ship of State with a rudder; the Latin word for rudder is gubernaculum.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Pharaonic times, the governors of each of the various provinces in the kingdoms of Upper and Lower Egypt (called "nomes" by the Greeks, and whose names often alluded to local patterns of religious worship) are usually known by the Greek word "nomarch," which was later used by historians.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Similarly, the term "*Haty-a"* (governor, mayor, overseer of priests, or overseer of the god's house) was referenced in inscriptions found in tombs, including those of Ankhtifi and Djefaihapi.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From the creation of the earliest Roman subject provinces, a governor was appointed each year to administer each of them.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The core function of a Roman governor was as a magistrate or judge, and the management of taxation and the public spending in their area.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Under the Republic and the early Empire, however, a governor also commanded military forces in his province.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Republican governors were all men who had served in senior magistracies (the consulate or praetorship) in Rome in the previous year, and carried related titles as governor (*proconsul* or *propraetor*).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The *legatus* sometimes would appoint a prefect (later procurator), usually a man of equestrian rank, to act as his deputy in a subregion of the larger province: the infamous character of Pontius Pilate in the Christian Gospels was a governor of this sort.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A special case was Egypt, a rich 'private' domain and vital granary, where the emperor almost inherited the theocratic status of a pharaoh.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The emperor was represented there by a governor *sui generis* styled *praefectus augustalis*, a title evoking the religious cult of the emperor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The prestigious governorships of Africa and Asia remained with the title proconsul, and the special right to refer matters directly to the emperor; the *praefectus augustalis* in Alexandria and the *comes Orientis* in Antioch also retained special titles.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Otherwise, the governors of provinces had various titles, some known as *consularis*, some as *corrector*, while others as *praeses*.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Apart from Egypt and the East (*Oriens* – *viz* greater Syria), each diocese was directed by a governor known as a *vicarius*.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The prefectures were directed by *praefecti praetorio* (greatly transformed in their functions from their role in the early Empire).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] This system survived with few significant changes until the collapse of the empire in the West, and in the East, the breakdown of order with the Persian and Arab invasions of the seventh century.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] At that stage, a new kind of governor emerged, the Strategos.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] It was a role leading the themes which replaced provinces at this point, involving a return to the amalgamation of civil and military office which had been the practice under the Republic and the early Empire.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] While the Roman administration in the West was largely destroyed in the barbarian invasions, its model was remembered; this model became very influential through two particular vehicles: Roman law and the Christian Church.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the British Empire, a governor was originally an official appointed by the British monarch (or the cabinet) to oversee a crown colony and was the (sometimes notional) head of the colonial administration.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governors' powers varied from colony to colony, depending on its constitutional setup; while all colonies had a separate court system, the governor only had legislative power in colonies that lacked a Legislative Council or Legislative Assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Today, crown colonies of the United Kingdom continue to be administered by governors who hold varying degrees of power.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Because of the different constitutional histories of the former colonies of the United Kingdom, the term *governor* now refers to officials with differing amounts of power.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Administrators, commissioners and high commissioners exercise similar powers to governors.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] (Note: such high commissioners are not to be confused with the high commissioners who are the equivalent of ambassadors between Commonwealth states).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Frequently the name 'Government House' is given to governors' residences.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Australia, each state has the governor as its formal representative of the sovereign, as head of the state government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] It is not a political office but a ceremonial one.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each state governor is appointed by the Australian monarch on the advice of the premier, who is the political chief executive of the state government (until 1986, state governors were appointed by the British monarch on the advice of the British government).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] State governors have emergency reserve powers but these are rarely used.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The territories of Australia other than the ACT have administrators instead of governors, who are appointed formally by the governor-general.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor-general is the representative of and appointed by the King of Australia sovereign at a federal level on the advice of the prime minister of Australia.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] As with the governors-general of Australia and other Commonwealth realms, state governors usually exercise their power only on the advice of a government minister.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each governor was appointed by the monarch and possessed significant powers such as the power of appointing lawmakers in the legislative council, the power to grant land, the power of veto over bills and motions, the power of pardon, etc.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] At the same time, the governor was also the head of the colonial cabinet, the chairman of the Executive Council, the president of the Legislative Council (until 1993), as well as the commander-in-chief of the British Forces in Hong Kong.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the United Kingdom's remaining overseas territories, the governor is normally a direct appointee of the British government and plays an active role in governing and lawmaking (though usually with the advice of elected local representatives).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor's chief responsibility is for the defence and external affairs of the colony.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In some minor overseas territories, instead of a governor, there is an administrator or commissioner, or the position is held *ex officio* by a High Commissioner.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Canada, there are governors at the federal and provincial levels of government who, within their jurisdictions, act as representatives of the king of Canada, who is Canada's head of state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The federal governor is the governor general of Canada, and the governor of each province is the lieutenant governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor general is appointed by the sovereign on the advice of the prime minister of Canada, whereas the lieutenant governors are appointed by the governor general on the advice of the prime minister.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The role of the governor general and of the lieutenant governors in Canada is largely ceremonial, although they do retain the authority to exercise reserve powers in exceptional circumstances.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each of the three territories is headed by a commissioner appointed by the federal Cabinet.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Unlike provincial lieutenant governors, they are not representatives of the sovereign but rather are representatives of the federal government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor-general of New Zealand is always the governor of the Ross Dependency, an Antarctic sector which is claimed by the Realm of New Zealand.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Within the United Kingdom itself, there was a position of Governor of Northern Ireland from 1922 until the suspension of the devolved Parliament of Northern Ireland in 1973.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From the 16th century until 1995, there was a governor of the Isle of Wight, part of England.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Since the reign of Henry VIII, the monarch has borne the title of Supreme Governor of the Church of England.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] European powers other than the United Kingdom, with colonies in Asia, Africa and elsewhere, gave their top representatives in their colonies the title of governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Those representatives could be from chartered companies that ruled the colonies.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In some of these colonies, there are still officials called governors.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the Russian Empire, the governorate (guberniya) and governorate-general were the main units of territorial and administrative subdivision since the reforms of Peter the Great.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] These were governed by a governor and governor-general respectively.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A special case was the Chinese Eastern Railway Zone, which was governed as a concession granted by Imperial China to the Russian 'Chinese Eastern Railway Society' (in Russian *Obshchestvo Kitayskoy Vostochnoy Zheleznoy Dorogi*; established on 17 December 1896 in St.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The post continued to function despite various political changes until after World War II.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Some of the administrative subdivisions of Russia are headed by governors, while others are headed by presidents or heads of administration.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From 1991 to 2005, they were elected by popular vote and from 2005 to 2012, they were appointed by the federal president and confirmed by the province's legislature.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] After the debate, conducted by State Duma in April 2012, the direct elections of governors were expected to be restored.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A Landeshauptmann (German for "state captain" or "state governor", literally 'country headman'; plural *Landeshauptleute* or *Landeshauptmänner* as in Styria till 1861; *Landeshauptfrau* is the female form) is an official title in German for certain political offices equivalent to a governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] It has historical uses, both administrative and colonial, and is now used in federal Austria and in South Tyrol, a majority German-speaking province of Italy adjacent to Tyrol.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] During the Ancien Régime in France, the representative of the king in his provinces and cities was the ***gouverneur***.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Royal officers were chosen from the highest nobility, and provincial and city governors (oversight of provinces and cities was frequently combined) were predominantly military positions in charge of defense and policing.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Provincial governors – also called "lieutenant generals" – also had the ability to convoke provincial parlements, provincial estates and municipal bodies.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The title "gouverneur" first appeared under Charles VI.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The ordinance of Blois of 1579 reduced their number to 12, but an ordinance of 1779 increased their number to 39 (18 first-class governors, 21 second-class governors).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Although in principle, they were the king's representatives and their charges could be revoked at the king's will, some governors had installed themselves and their heirs as a provincial dynasty.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Until 1933, the term *Landeshauptmann* (state governor) was used in Prussia for the head of government of a province, In the modern-day states of Germany, the counterpart to *Landeshauptmann* is the *Ministerpräsident* (minister-president).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the present German states of Baden-Württemberg, Bavaria, Hesse, and North Rhine-Westphalia there are – and earlier in more German states there were – sub-state administrative regions called in German: *Regierungsbezirk*, which is sometimes translated into English as governorate.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Thus its respective head, in German: *Regierungspräsident*, is also translated as governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Ioannis Kapodistrias was the first (and, with the exception of the short tenure of his younger brother Augustinos Kapodistrias, the only) head of state of Greece to bear the title of governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the People's Republic of China, the title *Governor* (Chinese: 省长; pinyin: *shěngzhǎng*) refers to the highest ranking executive of a provincial government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is usually placed second in the provincial power hierarchy, below the secretary of the provincial Chinese Communist Party (CCP) committee (省委书记), who serves as the highest ranking party official in the province.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Governors are elected by the provincial congresses and approved by the provincial party chief.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] All governors are not locals in the provinces which they govern.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The title can be also used while referring to a county governor (县长).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In India, each state has a ceremonial governor appointed by the president of India.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] These governors are different from the governors who controlled the British-controlled portions of the Indian Empire (as opposed to the princely states) prior to 1947.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A governor is the head of a state in India.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Generally, a governor is appointed for each state, but after the 7th Constitutional Amendment, of 1956, one governor can be appointed for more than one state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Indonesia, the title *gubernur* refers to the highest-ranking executive of a provincial government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor and the vice governor are elected by a direct vote from the people as a couple candidate, so the governor is responsible to the provincial residents.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor has a term of five years to work in office and can be re-elected for another single period.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In case of death, disability, or resignation, the vice governor would stand in as acting governor for some time before being inaugurated as the permanent governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The elected governor is inaugurated by the president, or by the Indonesian minister of home affairs on behalf of the president.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In addition, the governor is the representative of the central government in the province and is responsible to the president.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor's authority is regulated within Law (Indonesian: *Undang-undang*) No.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] 32/2004 and Governmental Ordinance (Indonesian: *Peraturan Pemerintah*) No.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Principally, the governor has the tasks and the authorities to lead governmental services in the province, based upon the policies that have been made together with the provincial parliament.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is not the superordinate of regents or mayors, but only guides supervises, and coordinates the works of city/municipal and regency governments.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In other parts, municipal and regency governments have the right to manage each governance affairs based on the autonomy principle and assistantship duties.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Japan, the title *Governor* (知事, *chiji*) refers to the highest ranking executive of a prefectural government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor was elected by a direct vote from the people and had a fixed term of four years.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] There is no restriction on the number of terms a person may serve as governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor holds considerable power within the prefecture, including the ability to veto ordinances that have been passed by the prefecture assembly, as well as control of the prefecture's budget and the power to dissolve the prefecture assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor can be subjected to a recall referendum.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A total of one to four vice governors are appointed by the governor with the approval of the assembly.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the case of the governor's death, disability, or resignation, a vice governor would stand in as governor or acting governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] See List of governors of Japan for a list of the current governors.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each of these states has a separate head of government called the *Ketua Menteri* or chief minister.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The four Yang di-Pertua Negeri are members of the Conference of Rulers; however, they cannot participate in the election of the Yang di-Pertuan Agong, discussions related to the privileges of the Malay rulers and matters concerning the observance of Islam.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Pakistan, each of the four provinces has a governor who is appointed by the president.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is the representative of the federal in their province and is the ceremonial head of the province whereas the chief minister is the head of the provincial government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor exercises powers similar to the president's, in their respective province.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the Philippines, the highest-ranking executive of a province is styled *Governor* (*Gobernador* or *Punong Lalawigan* in Filipino).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is elected by direct vote of the people with a fixed term of three years.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A governor can serve only up to a maximum of three consecutive terms.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] He may, however, be suspended by either the ombudsman or the President through the secretary of the interior and local government.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] He may be removed by the President if found guilty of an administrative case or a criminal act during his tenure.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] He may be subjected to a recall vote, but unlike a referendum, the voters elect the governor of their choice.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In case of death, disability, resignation, forced removal, or suspension, the vice governor, elected separately in the same election for governor, succeeds as governor, or acting governor, as the case may be.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] During both the Spanish and American colonial periods, as well as during the Japanese occupation of World War II, the chief executive of the Philippines was the Governor-general of the Philippines.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The highest ranking executive of the former Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao was called *regional governor,* elected for a term of three years and if vacating office, replaced by a regional vice-governor.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Bangsamoro, its replacement, has the *Wa'lī* (Arabic for "governor") as ceremonial head of the region, elected by parliament for a six-year term.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The provincial councils of the nine provinces of Sri Lanka are headed by governors, as representatives of the president.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Prior to 1948, in Ceylon (former name for Sri Lanka), the governor of Ceylon was the head of the British colony.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Thailand, the title *Governor* (ผู้ว่าราชการ *Phuwa Ratcha Gaan* in Thai) refers to the administrator of each Thai province, who is appointed by the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The only exception is the specially governed district of Bangkok, whose governor is elected by its population.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Mexico, *governor* refers to the elected leader of each of the nation's thirty-one Free and Sovereign States with the official Spanish title being *Gobernador*.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Mexican governors are directly elected by the citizens of each state for a six-year term and cannot be re-elected.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the United States, the title "Governor" refers to the head of each state or insular territory.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Governors retain sovereign power over executive and judiciary, are subordinate to the president of the United States and laws provided by the enumerated powers section of the federal constitution, and serve as the political and ceremonial head of the state.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Nearly three-fourths of the states (36) hold gubernatorial elections in the same years as midterm elections (two years offset from presidential elections).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Eleven states hold them in the same years as presidential elections (Vermont and New Hampshire hold elections every two years in every even-numbered year), while the remaining five hold them in odd-numbered years (two in the year after a presidential election, three in the year before).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In colonial North America, governors were chosen in a variety of ways, depending on how the colony was organized.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the crown colonies of Great Britain, France, and Spain, the governor was chosen by the ruling monarch of the colonizing power or his designees; in British colonies, the Board of Trade was often the primary decision maker.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Colonies based on a corporate charter, such as the Connecticut Colony and the Massachusetts Bay Colony, elected their own governors based on rules spelt out in the charter or other colonial legislation.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In proprietary colonies, such as the Province of Carolina before it became a crown colony (and was divided into North and South), governors were chosen by the Lords Proprietor who controlled the colony.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the early years of the American Revolutionary War, eleven of the Thirteen Colonies evicted (with varying levels of violence) royal and proprietary governors.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The other two colonies (Connecticut and Rhode Island) had corporate charters; Connecticut Governor Jonathan Trumbull was governor before and during the war period, while in Rhode Island, Governor Joseph Wanton was removed from office in 1775 for failing to support the rebel war effort.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Before achieving statehood, many of the fifty states were territories.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Administered by the federal government, they had governors who were appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate rather than elected by the resident population.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Papua New Guinea, the leaders of the provinces have been known as governors since August 1995.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Many of the South American republics (such as Chile and Argentina) have provinces or states run by elected governors, with offices similar in nature to U.S. state governors.
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Until the 1930 Revolution, the heads of the Brazilian Provinces, now called States, were styled as (provincial/state) presidents (*presidentes*).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From 1930 to 1945, they were styled either governors (*governadores*) or, when appointed by the federal government, intervenors (*interventores*).
[src:1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From 1945 on, they have only been called governors.
